  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA80-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu cēṭpaṭukkap paṭṭāṉāya talaivaṉ ṟōḻi kēṭpat taṉṉeñciṟ kuraittatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is what HE, who was being kept at a distance, said to his heart while the confidante was listening.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA80">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            maṉṟa verumai malartalaik kārā</l>
<l>            ṉiṉṟīm pāṟpayaṅ koṇmār kaṉṟuviṭ</l>
<l>            ṭūrkkuṟu mākkaṇ mēṟkoṇṭu kaḻiyum</l>
<l>            perumpular viṭiyaliṉ virumpip pōttantu</l>
<l>            taḻaiyun tārun tantaṉa ṉivaṉeṉa </l>
<l>            viḻaiyaṇi yāyamoṭu takunāṇ taṭaiit</l>
<l>            taiit tiṅkaṭ ṭaṇkayam paṭiyum</l>
<l>            peruntōṭ kuṟumaka ḷallatu</l>
<l>            maruntupiṟi tillaiyā ṉuṟṟa nōykkē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>There is no other remedy for the pain I had</l>
<l rend="indent">besides the little woman with big shoulders</l>
<l rend="indent">who lets herself down in the cool pond during the month of Tai,<note place="foot">For women to bath in the month of Tai is, according to T.V.G., an austerity performed to gain certain benefits (in this case the acquisition of the right man); see also Kal. 59.10-13.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">bent down with befitting<note place="foot">Actually here the less well attested variant <term xml:lang="ta">tarunāṇ</term> makes better sense, since it allows for a clearer connection betweens lines 5 and 6: "bent down with shame brought [upon her] by [her] jewel-adorned companions by saying ..."</note> shame, together with [her] jewel-</l>
<l rend="indent">adorned companions,</l>
<l rend="indent3">[who] say “he gave [her] foliage and a garland”,</l>
<l rend="indent">going longingly at progressing(?)<note place="foot"><term xml:lang="ta">perum pular viṭiyaliṉ</term>: perhaps it is best to take the <term xml:lang="ta">perum</term> as an adverb to pular "to dawn", the meaning being then that HE only left when dawn was already well progressed (and that is why he was seen).</note> dawn,</l>
<l rend="indent2">when the little people from the village passed by, mounted</l>
<l rend="indent2">[on their animals], the calfs set free to take the yield of the </l>
<l rend="indent2">pleasing sweet milk of the flower-headed cows of the buffalos</l>
<l rend="indent3">in the village common.</l>
        </lg>
         </div>
          </body>
        </text>
